# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chicken-fight
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] A **chicken fight**, also known as **shoulder wars**, is an informal game, often played in a lake or swimming pool, characterized by one team member sitting on the shoulders of their team mate or riding piggy-back.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] The object of the game is to knock down or separate an opposing team through team effort.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] The person on top is considered to be the "attacker" while the person below is considered to be the "vehicle".
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] The person below may not use arms or hands and must rely on momentum to attack by running into the other team.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] The person on his/her shoulders is the "attacker" and may use any means possible of separating the other team or knocking them to the ground.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] If a team is separated or knocked down in any way, they are required to resign from the game and the last team to remain together is considered the winner.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] It is not uncommon for this game to be banned in swimming pools due to safety concerns.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] A similar Japanese game called ***kibasen*** (騎馬戦; literally "cavalry fight") is commonly played as part of an annual sports day event at elementary and junior high schools.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] It is a field event rather than a swimming event.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] In it, a team of four competitors work together, with three carrying the fourth, who wears a bandana (hachimaki) or hat.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] The team is defeated if they are knocked over or, more commonly, if their bandana/hat is removed by an opponent.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] Competitors are often divided into opposing red and white factions.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] In recent years some schools have removed physically demanding events such as the *kibasen* from sports day programs due to the risk of serious injury.
[src:chicken-fight/chicken-fight] In a 2003 incident a high school student in Fukuoka Prefecture was left quadriplegic after falling from his teammates' shoulders.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka is the capital and largest city of Fukuoka Prefecture, and the largest city on Kyūshū, with other major cities including Kitakyushu, Kurume, and Ōmuta.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture is located at the northernmost point of Kyūshū on the Kanmon Straits, connecting the Tsushima Strait and the Seto Inland Sea across from Yamaguchi Prefecture on the island of Honshu, and extends south towards the Ariake Sea.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture includes the former provinces of Chikugo, Chikuzen, and Buzen.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Kōra taisha, Sumiyoshi-jinja, and Hakozaki-gū are the chief Shinto shrines (*ichinomiya*) in the prefecture.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] There are several historically important Buddhist temples in the Prefecture.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Monks would sail back from China after completing their studies and establish temples in the heart of Hakata (now Fukuoka) City.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Monk Eisai founded Shōfuku-ji which is known today as the oldest zen temple in Japan, monk Kukai established Tocho-ji, and Joten-ji was built by Enni who is also known for bringing Udon noodles first to Japan.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The oldest temple is Kanzeon-ji that was founded by the Emperor in Dazaifu during the 7th century to honor his mother.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Kanzeon-ji together with Kaidan-in, that used to be part of the former, was one of the three distinct places in Japan where Buddhist monks could ordain.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] During the Tokugawa shogunate when the country was ruled by 300 local feudal lords (daimyo), an important daimyo, Arima Toyōji was relocated to this region and thus he moved his family temple to Kurume City.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] This zen temple is known today as Bairin-ji and is a main temple for zen practice in Fukuoka Prefecture and Kyushu.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] It is located on the West bank of Chiguko River, next to the Shinkansen station of Kurume city.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture faces the sea on three sides, bordering Saga, Ōita, and Kumamoto prefectures and facing Yamaguchi Prefecture across the Kanmon Straits.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] As of 1 April 2012, 18% of the land area of the prefecture was designated as natural parks: Setonaikai National Park, Genkai, Kitakyūshū, and Yaba-Hita-Hikosan quasi-national parks, and Chikugogawa, Chikuhō, Dazaifu, Sefuri Raizan, and Yabegawa Prefectural Natural Parks.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka includes the two largest cities on Kyūshū, Fukuoka and Kitakyushu, and much of Kyūshū's industry.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] It also includes a number of small islands near the north coast of Kyūshū.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka prefecture's main cities form one of Japan's main industrial centers, accounting for nearly 40% of the economy of Kyūshū.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] GDP exceeds 154 billion US dollars, comparable to that of a medium-sized country.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Major industries include automobiles, semiconductors, and steel.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka prefecture is where tire manufacturer Bridgestone and consumer electronics chain Best Denki were founded.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] One of Japan's top 5 universities, Kyushu University, is located in Fukuoka.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] According to October 2018 estimates, the population in Fukuoka Prefecture reached 5,111,494 inhabitants, making the prefecture the 9th most populated of Japan's 47 prefectures.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] It is one of the few prefectures with a steadily increasing population.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] According to the 2020 Census, the population of Fukuoka Prefecture was 5,135,214.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] While the population had been increasing for decades, it has recently entered a declining phase.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Based on the 2023 projections by the National Institute of Population and Social Security Research (IPSS), the population is estimated to have fallen to approximately 5,088,000 by 2025 and is projected to drop below the 5 million mark by 2030.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] According to the 2025 Census, the population of Fukuoka Prefecture was 5,081,879.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The population declined by 1.0% or 53,335 from 2020, matching previous projections.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture moved up from 9th to 8th most-populated in Japan, as Hokkaido has a much larger rate of decline.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The sports teams listed below are based in Fukuoka.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The prefecture hosts the Fukuoka International Cross Country competition.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The prefecture also hosted the Fukuoka Marathon, which was an elite marathon in which marathon world records were established twice during its 75-year existence.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture has the most designated yakuza groups among all of the prefectures, at five: the Kudo-kai, the Taishu-kai, the Fukuhaku-kai, the Dojin-kai and the Namikawa-kai.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Between 2004 and 2009, and in early 2011, Fukuoka Prefecture led the nation in gun-related incidents.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] These incidents were mostly related to the local yakuza syndicates, specifically the Kudo-kai, the Dojin-kai, and the Kyushu Seido-kai.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka Prefecture had the highest frequency of youth crime among the prefectures of Japan from 2003 to 2007.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] According to statistics from the national police, the crime rate in Fukuoka was the eighth-highest in 2017, lower than in Osaka, Tokyo, Hyogo, Aichi, Saitama, Chiba and Ibaraki.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The most popular place for tourism is Fukuoka City, especially during the Dontaku festival, which attracts millions of visitors from across Japan during Golden Week.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Fukuoka is the main shopping, dining, transportation and entertainment hub in Kyushu.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Dazaifu is popular for its many temples and historical sites, as well as the Kyushu National Museum.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Yanagawa is sometimes called "the Venice of Japan" for its boat tours on the abundant, calm rivers that wind through the city.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] Kitakyushu features one of the famous night views of Japan from atop Mt.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The Mojiko area features waterfront dining, a market, and several preserved historical buildings.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The Kanmon Kaikyo Tunnel which connects Kyushu (Moji ward, Kitakyushu) and Honshu (Shimonoseki) is free to walk through.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] The city center in Kokurakita ward contains the Riverwalk and Itsutsuya shopping complexes, Kokura castle, and the Uomachi Gintengai shopping arcade, the oldest shopping arcade in Japan.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] In the "19 best places to visit in 2019" published by the U.S.
[src:chicken-fight/fukuoka-prefecture] CNN, Fukuoka Prefecture was chosen as the only destination in Japan.
[src:chicken-fight/game] A **game** is an activity defined by a challenge and a set of rules, typically done for enjoyment, competition, or development.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games may be played informally or in professional competitive settings before audiences.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Popular formats include board games, card games, video games, and sports, distinguished from unstructured play by having rules.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Scholars have long debated the essence of games, with no single definition achieving universal acceptance.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games are a universal feature of human culture.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The Royal Game of Ur and Senet are among the oldest known games, dating back to at least 2600 BCE.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Throughout history, games have served as tools for entertainment, teaching, ritual, and socialization.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In the modern era, the global video game industry has grown to surpass both film and music in annual revenue, reflecting how central games have become to contemporary life.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Philosophically, games have attracted attention as a test case for the nature of rules and meaning.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Psychologists link play to cognitive development in children and to the intense, satisfying concentration called flow in adults.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Game theory uses the structure of games to model decision making in fields such as economics and evolutionary biology.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Ludwig Wittgenstein is well known in the history of philosophy for having addressed the definition of the word *game*.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In his *Philosophical Investigations*, Wittgenstein argued that the elements of games, such as play, rules, and competition, all fail to adequately define what games are.
[src:chicken-fight/game] From this, Wittgenstein concluded that people apply the term *game* to a range of disparate human activities that bear to one another only what one might call family resemblances.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Bernard Suits offers this definition of games in *Grasshopper: Games, Life and Utopia* (1978).
[src:chicken-fight/game] The history of games goes back millennia.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The Royal Game of Ur, from ancient Mesopotamia in roughly 2600 BCE, is among the oldest known board games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] A cuneiform tablet from the 2nd century BCE contained its rules, representing the earliest recorded game design.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Senet, a board game played in ancient Egypt, was important enough to be portrayed in tomb artwork with fragments of the board found from approximately 3100 BCE.
[src:chicken-fight/game] A game board inscribed for Amenhotep III (c.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Both were race games and precursors to backgammon.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Senet had religious significance with the board representing the pathway through the netherworld.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In East Asia, the board game Go has written accounts as early as the Spring and Autumn period.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Go's strategic complexity resisted computation until deep learning advances in AlphaGo.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Other ancient games include mancala, a count-and-capture game with Neolithic versions found in Jordan from approximately 6900 BCE.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Chess traces back to the Gupta Empire of India around the 6th century CE with chaturanga a likely ancestor.
[src:chicken-fight/game] It spread through Persia as chatrang, and entered Europe via the Moorish Spain, approaching its modern form by the 15th century.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Playing cards may date to Tang dynasty China (618–907 CE), reaching Europe via the Mamluk Sultanate in the 14th century.
[src:chicken-fight/game] With mass production, standardized regional decks eventually evolved.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Pachisi, played in the Mughal court, served as the basis for Parcheesi and Ludo.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The Aztecs in Central America played a race game called patolli.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In the 20th century, developments included the rise of mass-market tabletop games such as Monopoly, Scrabble, Clue, and Trivial Pursuit and the emergence of video games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Pong, the first commercially successful arcade video game appeared in 1972.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In the 21st century, the global video game industry had grown to surpass film and music in annual revenue.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games can be characterized by "what the player does".
[src:chicken-fight/game] Major key elements identified in this context are tools and rules that define the overall context of game.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games are often classified by the components required to play them.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Common categories include tabletop games (using boards, cards, tokens, dice, or other items), card games (using a standard deck or game-specific cards), dice games, video games (using electronic hardware), and games with no equipment like hide-and-seek.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Game tokens are the means used to manage resources and achieve goals.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Pieces in a board game, cards in a card game, and characters in a role-playing game are tokens.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The ball has been a popular game piece for millennia, resulting in a worldwide popularity of ball games such as rugby, basketball, soccer (football), cricket, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Other tools are more idiosyncratic to a certain region.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Playing cards in Europe had decks with suits that varied from country to country before standardization.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Other games, such as chess, may be traced primarily through the development and evolution of their game pieces.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Game structures include boundaries, rules, goals, and scoring systems.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Game rules specify how actions are allowed to work.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The rules of a game may be distinguished from its aims.
[src:chicken-fight/game] For most competitive games, the *ultimate* aim is winning: in this sense, checkmate is the aim of chess.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Common win conditions are being the first to amass a certain quota of points or tokens (as in Settlers of Catan), having the greatest number of tokens at the end of the game (as in Monopoly), or some relationship of one's game tokens to those of one's opponent (as in chess's checkmate).
[src:chicken-fight/game] Intermediate goals can provide motivation when long-term goals may be far off.
[src:chicken-fight/game] An aim identifies a sufficient condition for successful action, whereas the rule identifies a necessary condition for permissible action.
[src:chicken-fight/game] For example, the aim of chess is to checkmate, but although it is expected that players will *try* to checkmate each other, it is not a rule of chess that a player *must* checkmate the other player whenever possible.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Some games include rules about changing rules.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In Nomic, invented by philosopher Peter Suber, players' turns include proposing rule changes and voting upon them.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games are commonly classified along the chance/skill spectrum.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Winning in chess is based on skill, while in Candy Land, it is based on luck.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Backgammon combines strategy with the chance of dice roll.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Settlers of Catan offers several paths to victory, and players may switch strategies, increasing their perceived autonomy.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games can take a variety of forms, from competitive sports to board games and video games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Sports are competitive games involving physical skill with accepted rules.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Many sports require special equipment and dedicated playing fields, leading to the involvement of a community much larger than the group of players.
[src:chicken-fight/game] A city or town may set aside such resources for the organization of sports leagues.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Association football (soccer) is the world's most popular sport by participation, with 250 million players in over 200 countries.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Spectator sports have been part of human culture for thousands of years.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Local and national sports teams are arenas for group identity, promoting civic pride in the home team in municipal rivalries.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Lawn games spread in the late 19th century as outdoor recreation.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Croquet, bocce, and boules provide leisurely competition and social interaction.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Tabletop games are designed to be played on a table, including board games, card games, and dice games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Board games use as a central tool a board on which location, interactions, and choices are tracked.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Abstract strategy games, such as chess and Go, are entirely determined by player moves not chance.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Race games such as Parcheesi and backgammon incorporate dice rolls, while Settlers of Catan involves resource management, trading, and negotiating with other players.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Board games have grown more dynamic in the 21st century, with Eurogames emphasizing efficient resource management over direct conflict.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Tens of thousands of tabletop games have launched on crowdfunding platform Kickstarter, with projects raising funds to pay for a game's production.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Card games use a deck of cards as their central tool.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Standard 52-card decks support many varieties of games including trick-taking games such as bridge and whist.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Uno was originally played with standard decks and has since been commercialized with customized decks.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Variations of the standard deck exist across the world such as "French-suited" 32-card decks, tarot-derived 78-card decks, and Italian 40-card decks.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Collectible card games were pioneered by Magic: The Gathering in 1993, where players form decks and compete against others.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The market has grown to $1.5 billion in 2021.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Collectible card game booster packs are random, while living card game pack contents are known.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Dice games use randomized dice rolls as their central element.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Examples include Yahtzee, Farkle, and craps.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Dominoes, while tile-based rather than using dice, also uses draw-and-play mechanics.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Commercial video games were first available in the 1970s, though earlier games included Tennis for Two and Spacewar!.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Video games are interactive and may have a game engine simulating complex physics and environments.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Genres include action/shooter, fighting, and platform games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Massively multiplayer online role-playing games can support thousands of players simultaneously within a virtual world.
[src:chicken-fight/game] As of 2013, the MMORPG *World of Warcraft* had 36% market share.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Esports give away millions of dollars in prize money while millions of viewers watch across the world.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In role-playing games (RPGs), players enact fictional characters and collaboratively shape a narrative.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Gary Gygax and Dave Arneson created the first RPG Dungeons & Dragons in 1974.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Players make choices for their characters, with a dungeon master adjudicating things the rules don't cover.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Video game RPGs tend to run characters through a predetermined story line.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Most Final Fantasy games present a fantasy/science fiction narrative with hero's journey, while Dark Souls is known for difficult action sequences.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Psychologists have long recognized play as a fundamental developmental activity.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Jean Piaget described play as a way to experiment with different cognitive schemas and assimilate experience.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Lev Vygotsky emphasized play's effectiveness in communicative, narrative, and representational competence.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In adults, games serve a range of psychological functions.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi called flow a state of intense concentration and total immersion which boosts life satisfaction.
[src:chicken-fight/game] To help players achieve flow, games offer clear goals, immediate feedback, and balance challenge with skill.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Research into problematic gaming has grown alongside the video game industry.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In 2019, the World Health Organization designated gaming disorder as a mental disorder, with effects such as health problems, sleep loss, and social isolation.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Serious games are designed for training, education, or health care rather than entertainment.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Flight simulators are used for pilot training, mission rehearsal for military planners, and laparoscopic equipment simulators for surgery.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In formal education, game-based learning has received extensive research.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Well-designed educational games can improve knowledge retention and deepen understanding.
[src:chicken-fight/game] John Nash proved that games with several players have a stable solution provided that coalitions between players are disallowed.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Nash won the Nobel Prize for economics for this important result which extended von Neumann's theory of zero-sum games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Nash's stable solution is known as the Nash equilibrium.
[src:chicken-fight/game] If cooperation between players is allowed, then the game becomes more complex; many concepts have been developed to analyze such games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Cooperative game theory uses coalition formation, joint actions, and payoffs for analysis.
[src:chicken-fight/game] In quantum game theory, it has been found that the introduction of quantum information into multiplayer games allows a new type of equilibrium strategy not found in traditional games.
[src:chicken-fight/game] The entanglement of player's choices can have the effect of a contract by preventing players from profiting from what is known as *betrayal*.
[src:chicken-fight/game] Games with many independent players are difficult to analyze formally using game theory as the players may form and switch coalitions.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] "helmet-scarf") is a type of Japanese headband, usually made of red or white cloth, typically featuring a design of kanji at the front.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] The origin of the *hachimaki* is uncertain, but the most common theory states that they originated as headbands used by samurai, worn underneath the *kabuto* to protect the wearer from cuts and to absorb sweat.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] Inspired by samurai, *kamikaze* pilots in World War II wore *hachimaki* while flying to their deaths.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] In modern Japan, *hachimaki* are often emblazoned with slogans and red circles reminiscent of the flag of Japan.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] They serve the function of absorbing sweat during physical activity, so they are often worn by sportspeople.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] *Hachimaki* may be worn to showcase Japanese nationalism or sporting pride.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] They are also associated with the *Bōsōzoku* subculture in Japan.
[src:chicken-fight/hachimaki] In Western popular culture, *hachimaki* are stereotypically associated with martial artists.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A **lake** is often a naturally occurring, relatively large and fixed body of water on or near the Earth's surface.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] It is localized in a basin or interconnected basins surrounded by dry land.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes lie completely on land and are separate from the ocean, although they may be connected with the ocean by rivers.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes, like other bodies of water, are part of the water cycle, the processes by which water moves around the Earth.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Most lakes are fresh water and account for almost all the world's surface freshwater, but some are salt lakes with salinities even higher than that of seawater.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes vary significantly in surface area and volume of water, but in total cover approximately 2.5 X 106 km2 (less than 2%) of the Earth's surface.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes are typically larger and deeper than ponds, which are also water-filled basins on land, although there are no official definitions or scientific criteria distinguishing the two.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes are also distinct from lagoons, which are generally shallow tidal pools dammed by sandbars or other material at coastal regions of oceans or large lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Most lakes are fed by springs, and both fed and drained by creeks and rivers, but some lakes are endorheic without any outflow, while volcanic lakes are filled directly by precipitation runoffs and do not have any inflow streams.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Natural lakes are generally found in mountainous areas (i.e. alpine lakes), dormant volcanic craters, rift zones and areas with ongoing glaciation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Other lakes are found in depressed landforms or along the courses of mature rivers, where a river channel has widened over a basin formed by eroded floodplains and wetlands.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some lakes are found in caverns underground.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some parts of the world have many lakes formed by the chaotic drainage patterns left over from the last ice age.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] All lakes are temporary over long periods of time, as they will slowly fill in with sediments or spill out of the basin containing them.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Artificially controlled lakes are known as reservoirs, and are usually constructed for industrial or agricultural use, for hydroelectric power generation, for supplying domestic drinking water, for ecological or recreational purposes, or for other human activities.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The word *lake* comes from Middle English *lake* ('lake, pond, waterway'), from Old English *lacu* ('pond, pool, stream'), from Proto-Germanic **lakō* ('pond, ditch, slow moving stream'), from the Proto-Indo-European root **leǵ-* ('to leak, drain').
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Cognates include Dutch *laak* ('lake, pond, ditch'), Middle Low German *lāke* ('water pooled in a riverbed, puddle') as in: de:Wolfslake, de:Butterlake, Modern Low German *Laak* ('pool, puddle'), German *Lache* ('pool, puddle'), and Icelandic *lækur* ('slow flowing stream').
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Also related are the English words *leak* and *leach*.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] There is considerable uncertainty about defining the difference between lakes and ponds, and neither term has an internationally accepted definition across scientific disciplines or political boundaries.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] For example, limnologists have defined lakes as water bodies that are simply a larger version of a pond, which can have wave action on the shoreline or where wind-induced turbulence plays a major role in mixing the water column.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] None of these definitions completely excludes ponds and all are difficult to measure.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] For this reason, simple size-based definitions are increasingly used to separate ponds and lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Definitions for *lake* range in minimum sizes for a body of water from 2 hectares (5 acres) to 8 hectares (20 acres).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Pioneering animal ecologist Charles Elton regarded lakes as waterbodies of 40 hectares (99 acres) or more.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The term *lake* is also used to describe a feature such as Lake Eyre, which is a dry basin most of the time but may become filled under seasonal conditions of heavy rainfall.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In common usage, many lakes bear names ending with the word *pond*, and a lesser number of names ending with *lake* are, in quasi-technical fact, ponds.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The area measured at the mean water level exceeds an arbitrarily chosen threshold (for instance, one hectare).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] With the exception of criterion 3, the others have been accepted or elaborated upon by other hydrology publications.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The majority of lakes on Earth are freshwater, and most lie in the Northern Hemisphere at higher latitudes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Canada, with a deranged drainage system, has an estimated 31,752 lakes larger than 3 square kilometres (1.2 sq mi) in surface area.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The total number of lakes in Canada is unknown but is estimated to be at least 2 million.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Finland has 168,000 lakes of 500 square metres (5,400 sq ft) in area, or larger, of which 57,000 are large (10,000 square metres (110,000 sq ft) or larger).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Most lakes have at least one natural outflow in the form of a river or stream, which maintain a lake's average level by allowing the drainage of excess water.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some lakes do not have a natural outflow and lose water solely by evaporation or underground seepage, or both.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Many lakes are artificial and are constructed for hydroelectric power generation, aesthetic purposes, recreational purposes, industrial use, agricultural use, or domestic water supply.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The number of lakes on Earth is undetermined because most lakes and ponds are very small and do not appear on maps or satellite imagery.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Despite this uncertainty, a large number of studies agree that small ponds are much more abundant than large lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] For example, one widely cited study estimated that Earth has 304 million lakes and ponds, and that 91% of these are 1 hectare (2.5 acres) or less in area.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Despite the overwhelming abundance of ponds, almost all of Earth's lake water is found in fewer than 100 large lakes; this is because lake volume scales superlinearly with lake area.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Extraterrestrial lakes exist on the moon Titan, which orbits the planet Saturn.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The shape of lakes on Titan is very similar to those on Earth.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes were formerly present on the surface of Mars, but are now dry lake beds.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Evelyn Hutchinson published a monograph titled *A Treatise on Limnology*, which is regarded as a landmark discussion and classification of all major lake types, their origin, morphometric characteristics, and distribution.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Hutchinson presented in his publication a comprehensive analysis of the origin of lakes and proposed what is a widely accepted classification of lakes according to their origin.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This classification recognizes 11 major lake types that are divided into 76 subtypes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Tectonic lakes are lakes formed by the deformation and resulting lateral and vertical movements of the Earth's crust.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These movements include faulting, tilting, folding, and warping.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some of the largest lakes on Earth are rift lakes occupying rift valleys, e.g.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Central African Rift lakes and Lake Baikal.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Other well-known tectonic lakes, Caspian Sea, the Sea of Aral, and other lakes from the Pontocaspian occupy basins that have been separated from the sea by the tectonic uplift of the sea floor above the ocean level.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Often, the tectonic action of crustal extension has created an alternating series of parallel grabens and horsts that form elongate basins alternating with mountain ranges.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Not only does this promote the creation of lakes by the disruption of preexisting drainage networks, it also creates within arid regions endorheic basins that contain salt lakes (also called saline lakes).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They form where there is no natural outlet, a high evaporation rate and the drainage surface of the water table has a higher-than-normal salt content.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Examples of these salt lakes include Great Salt Lake and the Dead Sea.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Another type of tectonic lake caused by faulting is sag ponds.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Volcanic lakes are lakes that occupy either local depressions, e.g. craters and maars, or larger basins, e.g. calderas, created by volcanism.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Crater lakes are formed in volcanic craters and calderas, which fill up with precipitation more rapidly than they empty via either evaporation, groundwater discharge, or a combination of both.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Sometimes the latter are called caldera lakes, although often no distinction is made.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] An example is Crater Lake in Oregon, in the caldera of Mount Mazama.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The caldera was created in a massive volcanic eruption that led to the subsidence of Mount Mazama around 4860 BC.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Other volcanic lakes are created when either rivers or streams are dammed by lava flows or volcanic lahars.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The basin which is now Malheur Lake, Oregon was created when a lava flow dammed the Malheur River.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Among all lake types, volcanic crater lakes most closely approximate a circular shape.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Glacial lakes are lakes created by the direct action of glaciers and continental ice sheets.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A wide variety of glacial processes create enclosed basins.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] As a result, there are a wide variety of different types of glacial lakes and it is often difficult to define clear-cut distinctions between different types of glacial lakes and lakes influenced by other activities.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The general types of glacial lakes that have been recognized are lakes in direct contact with ice, glacially carved rock basins and depressions, morainic and outwash lakes, and glacial drift basins.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Glacial lakes are the most numerous lakes in the world.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Most lakes in northern Europe and North America have been either influenced or created by the latest, but not last, glaciation, to have covered the region.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Glacial lakes include proglacial lakes, subglacial lakes, finger lakes, and epishelf lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Epishelf lakes are highly stratified lakes in which a layer of freshwater, derived from ice and snow melt, is dammed behind an ice shelf that is attached to the coastline.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Fluvial (or riverine) lakes are lakes produced by running water.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These lakes include plunge pool lakes, fluviatile dams and meander lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The most common type of fluvial lake is a crescent-shaped lake called an *oxbow lake* due to the distinctive curved shape.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They can form in river valleys as a result of meandering.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The slow-moving river forms a sinuous shape as the outer side of bends are eroded away more rapidly than the inner side.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Eventually a horseshoe bend is formed and the river cuts through the narrow neck.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This new passage then forms the main passage for the river and the ends of the bend become silted up, thus forming a bow-shaped lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Their crescent shape gives oxbow lakes a higher perimeter to area ratio than other lake types.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These form where sediment from a tributary blocks the main river.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These form where sediment from the main river blocks a tributary, usually in the form of a levee.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes formed by other processes responsible for floodplain basin creation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] During high floods they are flushed with river water.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Contrafluent-confluent floodplain lake, 3.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A solution lake is a lake occupying a basin formed by surface dissolution of bedrock.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In areas underlain by soluble bedrock, its solution by precipitation and percolating water commonly produce cavities.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These cavities frequently collapse to form sinkholes that form part of the local karst topography.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Where groundwater lies near the grounds surface, a sinkhole will be filled water as a solution lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] If such a lake consists of a large area of standing water that occupies an extensive closed depression in limestone, it is also called a karst lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A landslide lake is created by the blockage of a river valley by either mudflows, rockslides, or screes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Such lakes are most common in mountainous regions.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Although landslide lakes may be large and quite deep, they are typically short-lived.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] An example of a landslide lake is Quake Lake, which formed as a result of the 1959 Hebgen Lake earthquake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Most landslide lakes disappear in the first few months after formation, but a landslide dam can burst suddenly at a later stage and threaten the population downstream when the lake water drains out.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In 1911, an earthquake triggered a landslide that blocked a deep valley in the Pamir Mountains region of Tajikistan, forming the Sarez Lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The Usoi Dam at the base of the valley has remained in place for more than 100 years but the terrain below the lake is in danger of a catastrophic flood if the dam were to fail during a future earthquake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Tal-y-llyn Lake in north Wales is a landslide lake dating back to the last glaciation in Wales some 20,000 years ago.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Aeolian lakes are produced by wind action.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These lakes are found mainly in arid environments, although some aeolian lakes are relict landforms indicative of arid paleoclimates.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Aeolian lakes consist of lake basins dammed by wind-blown sand; interdunal lakes that lie between well-oriented sand dunes; and deflation basins formed by wind action under previously arid paleoenvironments.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Moses Lake in Washington, United States, was originally a shallow natural lake and an example of a lake basin dammed by wind-blown sand.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] China's Badain Jaran Desert is a unique landscape of megadunes and elongated interdunal aeolian lakes, particularly concentrated in the southeastern margin of the desert.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Shoreline lakes are generally lakes created by blockage of estuaries or by the uneven accretion of beach ridges by longshore and other currents.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They include maritime coastal lakes, ordinarily in drowned estuaries; lakes enclosed by two tombolos or spits connecting an island to the mainland; lakes cut off from larger lakes by a bar; or lakes divided by the meeting of two spits.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Organic lakes are lakes created by the actions of plants and animals.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] On the whole they are relatively rare in occurrence and quite small in size.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In addition, they typically have ephemeral features relative to the other types of lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The basins in which organic lakes occur are associated with beaver dams, coral lakes, or dams formed by vegetation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They form where a buildup of partly decomposed plant material in a wet environment leaves the vegetated surface below the water table for a sustained period of time.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They are often low in nutrients and mildly acidic, with bottom waters low in dissolved oxygen.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Artificial lakes or anthropogenic lakes are large waterbodies created by human activity.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] They can be formed by the intentional damming of rivers and streams, rerouting of water to inundate a previously dry basin, or the deliberate filling of abandoned excavation pits by either precipitation runoff, ground water, or a combination of both.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Artificial lakes may be used as storage reservoirs that provide drinking water for nearby settlements, to generate hydroelectricity, for flood management, for supplying agriculture or aquaculture, or to provide an aquatic sanctuary for parks and nature reserves.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The Upper Silesian region of southern Poland contains an anthropogenic lake district consisting of more than 4,000 water bodies created by human activity.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The diverse origins of these lakes include: reservoirs retained by dams, flooded mines, water bodies formed in subsidence basins and hollows, levee ponds, and residual water bodies following river regulation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Same for the Lusatian Lake District, Germany.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In India, Sudarshana Lake is a historical artificial lake located in the semi-arid region of Girnar, Gujarat, originally constructed during the reign of Chandragupta Maurya.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Meteorite lakes, also known as *crater lakes* (not to be confused with volcanic crater lakes), are created by catastrophic impacts with the Earth by extraterrestrial objects (either meteorites or asteroids).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Examples of meteorite lakes are Lonar Lake in India, Lake El'gygytgyn in northeast Siberia, and the Pingualuit crater lake in Quebec, Canada.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] As in the cases of El'gygytgyn and Pingualuit, meteorite lakes can contain unique and scientifically valuable sedimentary deposits associated with long records of paleoclimatic changes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The names used by the lay public and in the scientific community for different types of lakes are often informally derived from the morphology of the lakes' physical characteristics or other factors.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Also, different cultures and regions of the world have their own popular nomenclature.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] One important method of lake classification is on the basis of thermal stratification, which has a major influence on the animal and plant life inhabiting a lake, and the fate and distribution of dissolved and suspended material in the lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] For example, the thermal stratification, as well as the degree and frequency of mixing, has a strong control over the distribution of oxygen within the lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Forel, also referred to as the "Father of limnology", was the first scientist to classify lakes according to their thermal stratification.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] His system of classification was later modified and improved upon by Hutchinson and Löffler.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] As the density of water varies with temperature, with a maximum at +4 degrees Celsius, thermal stratification is an important physical characteristic of a lake that controls the fauna and flora, sedimentation, chemistry, and other aspects of individual lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] First, the colder, denser water typically forms a layer near the bottom, which is called the *hypolimnion*.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Second, normally overlying the hypolimnion is a transition zone known as the *metalimnion*.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Finally, overlying the metalimnion is a surface layer of warmer water with a lower density, called the *epilimnion*.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This typical stratification sequence can vary widely, depending on the specific lake or the time of year, or a combination of both.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The classification of lakes by thermal stratification presupposes lakes with sufficient depth to form a hypolimnion; accordingly, very shallow lakes are excluded from this classification system.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Based upon their thermal stratification, lakes are classified as either *holomictic*, with a uniform temperature and density from top to bottom at a given time of year, or *meromictic*, with layers of water of different temperature and density that do not intermix.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The deepest layer of water in a meromictic lake does not contain any dissolved oxygen so there are no living aerobic organisms.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Consequently, the layers of sediment at the bottom of a meromictic lake remain relatively undisturbed, which allows for the development of lacustrine deposits.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In a holomictic lake, the uniformity of temperature and density allows the lake waters to completely mix.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Based upon thermal stratification and frequency of turnover, holomictic lakes are divided into amictic lakes, cold monomictic lakes, dimictic lakes, warm monomictic lakes, polymictic lakes, and oligomictic lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lake stratification does not always result from a variation in density because of thermal gradients.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Stratification can also result from a density variation caused by gradients in salinity.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In this case, the hypolimnion and epilimnion are separated not by a thermocline but by a *halocline*, which is sometimes referred to as a *chemocline*.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes are informally classified and named according to the seasonal variation in their lake level and volume.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes may be informally classified and named according to the general chemistry of their water mass.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A **paleolake** (also **palaeolake**) is a lake that existed in the past when hydrological conditions were different.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The paleoshorelines and sedimentary deposits of paleolakes provide evidence for prehistoric hydrological changes during the times that they existed.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Paleolakes are of scientific and economic importance.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In addition, the organic-rich deposits of pre-Quaternary paleolakes are important either for the thick deposits of oil shale and shale gas contained in them, or as source rocks of petroleum and natural gas.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Although of significantly less economic importance, strata deposited along the shore of paleolakes sometimes contain coal seams.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes have numerous features in addition to lake type, such as drainage basin (also known as catchment area), inflow and outflow, nutrient content, dissolved oxygen, pollutants, pH, and sedimentation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Changes in the level of a lake are controlled by the difference between the input and output compared to the total volume of the lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Significant input sources are precipitation onto the lake, runoff carried by streams and channels from the lake's catchment area, groundwater channels and aquifers, and artificial sources from outside the catchment area.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Output sources are evaporation from the lake, surface and groundwater flows, and any extraction of lake water by humans.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] As climate conditions and human water requirements vary, these will create fluctuations in the lake level.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes can be also categorized on the basis of their richness in nutrients, which typically affect plant growth.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Nutrient-poor lakes are said to be *oligotrophic* and are generally clear, having a low concentration of plant life.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] *Mesotrophic lakes* have good clarity and an average level of nutrients.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] *Eutrophic* lakes are enriched with nutrients, resulting in good plant growth and possible algal blooms.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] *Hypertrophic* lakes are bodies of water that have been excessively enriched with nutrients.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These lakes typically have poor clarity and are subject to devastating algal blooms.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Lakes typically reach this condition due to human activities, such as heavy use of fertilizers in the lake catchment area.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Such lakes are of little use to humans and have a poor ecosystem due to decreased dissolved oxygen.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Due to the unusual relationship between water's temperature and its density, lakes form layers called thermoclines, layers of drastically varying temperature relative to depth.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Fresh water is most dense at about 4 degrees Celsius (39.2 °F) at sea level.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] When the temperature of the water at the surface of a lake reaches the same temperature as deeper water, as it does during the cooler months in temperate climates, the water in the lake can mix, bringing oxygen-starved water up from the depths and bringing oxygen down to decomposing sediments.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Deep temperate lakes can maintain a reservoir of cold water year-round, which allows some cities to tap that reservoir for deep lake water cooling.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Since the surface water of deep tropical lakes never reaches the temperature of maximum density, there is no process that makes the water mix.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The deeper layer becomes oxygen starved and can become saturated with carbon dioxide, or other gases such as sulfur dioxide if there is even a trace of volcanic activity.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Exceptional events, such as earthquakes or landslides, can cause mixing which rapidly brings the deep layers up to the surface and release a vast cloud of gas which lay trapped in solution in the colder water at the bottom of the lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] An example is the disaster at Lake Nyos in Cameroon.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The amount of gas that can be dissolved in water is directly related to pressure.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] As deep water surfaces, the pressure drops and a vast amount of gas comes out of solution.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Under these circumstances carbon dioxide is hazardous because it is heavier than air and displaces it, so it may flow down a river valley to human settlements and cause mass asphyxiation.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The material at the bottom of a lake, or *lake bed*, may be composed of a wide variety of inorganics, such as silt or sand, and organic material, such as decaying plant or animal matter.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The composition of the lake bed has a significant impact on the flora and fauna found within the lake's environs by contributing to the amounts and the types of nutrients available.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A paired (black and white) layer of the varved lake sediments correspond to a year.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] During winter, when organisms die, carbon is deposited down, resulting to a black layer.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] At the same year, during summer, only few organic materials are deposited, resulting to a white layer at the lake bed.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These are commonly used to track past paleontological events.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Natural lakes provide a microcosm of living and nonliving elements that are relatively independent of their surrounding environments.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Therefore, lake organisms can often be studied in isolation from the lake's surroundings.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Limnology is the study of inland bodies of water and related ecosystems.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Limnology divides lakes into three zones: the *littoral zone*, a sloped area close to land; the *photic* or *open-water zone*, where sunlight is abundant; and the deep-water *profundal* or *benthic zone*, where little sunlight can reach.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The depth to which light can penetrate depends on the turbidity of the water, which is determined by the density and size of suspended particles.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A particle will be in suspension if its weight is less than the random turbidity forces acting upon it.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These particles can be sedimentary or biological in origin (including algae and detritus) and are responsible for the color of the water.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Decaying plant matter, for instance, may account for a yellow or brown color, while algae may cause a greenish coloration.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In very shallow water bodies, iron oxides make the water reddish brown.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Bottom-dwelling detritivorous fish stir the mud in search of food and can be the cause of turbid waters.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Piscivorous fish contribute to turbidity by eating plant-eating (planktonivorous) fish, thus increasing the amount of algae (see aquatic trophic cascade).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The light depth or transparency is measured using a *Secchi disk*, a 20-cm (8 in) disk with alternating white and black quadrants.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The depth at which the disk is no longer visible is the *Secchi depth*, a measure of transparency.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The Secchi disk is commonly used to test for eutrophication.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] For a detailed look at these processes, see lentic ecosystems.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A lake moderates the surrounding region's temperature and climate because water has a very high specific heat capacity (4,186 J·kg−1·K−1).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In the daytime a lake can cool the land beside it with local winds, resulting in a sea breeze; in the night it can warm it with a land breeze.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The lake may be infilled with deposited sediment and gradually become a wetland such as a swamp or marsh.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Large water plants, typically reeds, accelerate this closing process significantly because they partially decompose to form peat soils that fill the shallows.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Conversely, peat soils in a marsh can naturally burn and reverse this process to recreate a shallow lake resulting in a dynamic equilibrium between marsh and lake.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This is significant since wildfire has been largely suppressed in the developed world over the past century.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This has artificially converted many shallow lakes into emergent marshes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Turbid lakes and lakes with many plant-eating fish tend to disappear more slowly.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A "disappearing" lake (barely noticeable on a human timescale) typically has extensive plant mats at the water's edge.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These become a new habitat for other plants, like peat moss when conditions are right, and animals, many of which are very rare.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Gradually, the lake closes and young peat may form, forming a fen.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In lowland river valleys where a river can meander, the presence of peat is explained by the infilling of historical oxbow lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] In the final stages of succession, trees can grow in, eventually turning the wetland into a forest.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] These are called **intermittent lakes**, **ephemeral lakes**, or **seasonal lakes** and can be found in karstic terrain.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A prime example of an intermittent lake is Lake Cerknica in Slovenia or Lag Prau Pulte in Graubünden.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Other intermittent lakes are only the result of above-average precipitation in a closed, or endorheic basin, usually filling dry lake beds.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This can occur in some of the driest places on earth, like Death Valley.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] This occurred in the spring of 2005, after unusually heavy rains.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The lake did not last into the summer, and was quickly evaporated (see photos to right).
[src:chicken-fight/lake] A more commonly filled lake of this type is Sevier Lake of west-central Utah.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Sometimes a lake will disappear quickly.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] On 3 June 2005, in Nizhny Novgorod Oblast, Russia, a lake called Lake Beloye vanished in a matter of minutes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] News sources reported that government officials theorized that this strange phenomenon may have been caused by a shift in the soil underneath the lake that allowed its water to drain through channels leading to the Oka River.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The presence of ground permafrost is important to the persistence of some lakes.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Thawing permafrost may explain the shrinking or disappearance of hundreds of large Arctic lakes across western Siberia.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The idea here is that rising air and soil temperatures thaw permafrost, allowing the lakes to drain away into the ground.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some lakes disappear because of human development factors.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The shrinking Aral Sea is described as being "murdered" by the diversion for irrigation of the rivers feeding it.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Between 1990 and 2020, more than half of the world's large lakes decreased in size, in part due to climate change.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Only one astronomical body other than Earth is known to harbor large lakes: Saturn's largest moon, Titan.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Photographs and spectroscopic analysis by the *Cassini–Huygens* spacecraft show liquid ethane on the surface, which is thought to be mixed with liquid methane.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The largest lake on Titan is Kraken Mare which, at an estimated 400,000 km2, is roughly five times the size of Lake Superior (~80,000 km2) and nearly the size of all five Great Lakes of North America combined.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The second largest Titanean lake, Ligeia Mare, is almost twice the size of Lake Superior, at an estimated 150,000 km2.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Jupiter's large moon Io is volcanically active, leading to the accumulation of sulfur deposits on the surface.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Some photographs taken during the *Galileo* mission appear to show lakes of liquid sulfur in volcanic caldera, though these are more analogous to lakes of lava than of water on Earth.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] The planet Mars has only one confirmed lake which is underground and near the south pole.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] Although the surface of Mars is too cold and has too little atmospheric pressure to permit permanent surface water, geologic evidence appears to confirm that ancient lakes once formed on the surface.
[src:chicken-fight/lake] There are dark basaltic plains on the Moon, similar to lunar maria but smaller, which are called *lacus* (singular *lacus*, Latin for "lake") because they were thought by early astronomers to be lakes of water.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] A person carrying someone else on their back is most commonly seen in the modern day in the form of a parent carrying their child, either for travelling or for children's games.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Piggybacking may also feature in the context of play or sport, and evidence of this dates back to Ancient Greece where games involving piggyback riding were combined with the requirement of catching or throwing a ball.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] In the modern era, wife carrying competitions, where the female participants ride on the back of their male partners running the race, are popular in some countries.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] In rail transport, the practice of carrying trailers or semi-trailers in a train atop a flatcar is referred to as "piggybacking".
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Early drawings of the Liverpool & Manchester Railway c1830 show road coaches being piggybacked on railway flat wagons.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The rail service provided for trucks which are carried on trains for part of their journey is referred to as a rolling road, or rolling highway.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] A related transportation method is the rail transport of semi-trailers, without road tractors, sometimes referred to as "trailer on flatcar (TOFC)".
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] In the United States, TOFC traffic grew from 1% of freight in 1957 to 5% in 1964 and 15% in 1986.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] A rail vehicle of one track gauge can be carried on a flatcar (transporter wagon or rollbock) of another gauge.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] In addition, an entire train of coupled cars of one gauge can be carried on continuous rails on a train of flatcars of another gauge.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] This was achieved, as a temporary expedient, by the Commonwealth Railways on the Marree railway line in South Australia between Telford Cut and Port Augusta in the mid-1950s.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Japan Railways planned a similar "Train on Train" scheme, but at much higher speeds, to operate from 2016.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] For semi trucks the trucks can be stacked 4 deep if it is just a day-cab truck and only 3 deep if it has a sleeper-cab.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The trucks drive up a ramp or are lifted into place by a tow hook on the front bumper, from a heavy-duty tow truck or overhead crane.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] A saddle is placed on the fifth-wheel, that the front axle of the next truck is attached to, which is called decking.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The mirrors are folded in on the trucks being hauled for width requirements and safety.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] For undecking the trucks, a tow truck or overhead crane is used again.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] It is typically used to transport newly built or purchased trucks.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Small ships of all kinds can be piggybacked on larger ships.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Examples include lifeboats, landing craft, and minesweepers on motherships, as well as midget submarines on larger submarines, such as those used for the 1942 Japanese submarine attack on Sydney.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] A piggyback microcontroller refers to a type of microcontroller setup where an external memory chip, typically an EPROM, is mounted directly on top of the microcontroller chip—often via a socket.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] This configuration allows for easy swapping or reprogramming of the firmware without replacing the entire microcontroller.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The 1930s British Short Mayo Composite, in which a smaller, four-engine floatplane aircraft named Mercury was carried aloft on the back of a larger four-engine flying boat named Maia, enabled the Mercury to achieve a greater range than would have been possible had it taken off under its own power.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The American Space Shuttle was carried on top of specially-modified Boeing 747 Shuttle Carrier Aircraft when the shuttle landed at places other than Kennedy Space Center.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] In space transportation systems, a smaller satellite that is carried as a secondary payload on a launch is said to be "piggybacked" on the main launch.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] It is often the case of small satellites and cubesats, since they can not usually afford accessing space on a dedicated launch and they choose instead to take profit of the remaining payload capacity in a big satellite launch.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] However, this is usually at the cost of not being able to fly to their desired orbit and having to remain on a similar orbit to that of the big satellite.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] The metal caterpillar treads of a tank wear out quickly when travelling long distances on ordinary roads.
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] Also, tracked vehicles seriously damage the tarmac layer of ordinary roads (unless the caterpillar treads are specially fitted with rubber pads to avoid this).
[src:chicken-fight/piggy-back-transportation] It is therefore necessary to provide tank transporters, which have rubber tires, to the battlefield.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Although the most obvious symptom is impairment of the limbs, functioning is also impaired in the trunk and pelvic organs.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This can lead to loss or impairment of controlling bowel and bladder, sexual function, digestion, breathing and other autonomic functions.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Furthermore, sensation is usually impaired in affected areas.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This may manifest as numbness, reduced sensation or neuropathic pain.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Secondarily, because of their depressed functioning and immobility, tetraplegics are often more vulnerable to pressure sores, osteoporosis and fractures, frozen joints, spasticity, respiratory complications, infections, autonomic dysreflexia, deep vein thrombosis, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The severity of the condition depends on both the level at which the spinal cord is injured and the extent of the injury.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] An individual with an injury at C1 (the highest cervical vertebra, at the base of the skull) will probably lose function from the neck down and be ventilator-dependent.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] An individual with a C7 injury may lose function from the chest down but still retain use of the arms and much of the hands.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] An individual in between, with a C5 injury may lose some function from the chest down and fine motor skills in their hands but still have flexion and extension abilities of certain muscles around the back or arm area.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The extent of the injury is also important.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] A complete severing of the spinal cord will result in complete loss of function from that vertebra down.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] A partial severing or even bruising of the spinal cord results in varying degrees of mixed function and paralysis.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] A common misconception with tetraplegia is that the victim cannot move legs, arms, or any other major body regions; this is often not the case.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Some tetraplegics can walk and use their hands, as though they did not have a spinal cord injury, while others may use wheelchairs and retain some functions in their arms and fingers; again, this varies based on the degree of damage to the spinal cord and is mostly seen with incomplete tetraplegia.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] It is common to have partial movement in limbs, such as the ability to move the arms but not the hands, or to be able to use the fingers but not to the same extent as before the injury.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Furthermore, the deficit in the limbs may not be the same on both sides of the body; either side may be more affected, depending on the location of the lesion on the spinal cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Another important factor is the possibility that the patient may exhibit sporadic movement in the affected areas.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] One of the main causes for this would be myoclonus, or muscle spasms.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] "After a spinal cord injury, the normal flow of signals is disrupted, and the message does not reach the brain.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Instead, the signals are sent back to the motor cells in the spinal cord and cause a reflex muscle spasm.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Tetraplegia is caused by damage to the brain or the spinal cord at a high level.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The injury, which is known as a lesion, causes the loss of partial or total function of all four limbs, meaning the arms and the legs.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Typical causes of this damage are trauma (such as a traffic collision, diving into shallow water, a fall, a sports injury), disease (such as transverse myelitis, Guillain–Barré syndrome, multiple sclerosis, or polio), or congenital disorders (such as muscular dystrophy).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Tetraplegia is defined in many ways; C1–C4 usually affects arm movement more so than a C5–C7 injury; however, all tetraplegics have or have had some kind of finger dysfunction.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] So, it is not uncommon to have a tetraplegic with fully functional arms but no nervous control of their fingers and thumbs.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] It is possible to have a broken neck without becoming tetraplegic if the vertebrae are fractured or dislocated but the spinal cord is not damaged.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Conversely, it is possible to injure the spinal cord without breaking the spine, for example when a ruptured disc or bone spur on the vertebra protrudes into the spinal column.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Since tetraplegia is defined as dysfunction in the cervical spinal cord, this section will focus on the anatomy of the cervical spinal cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] To understand how tetraplegia presents after injury, it is imperative to have a broad knowledge of the cervical spinal roots and its many functions.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In the cervical spine, nerve roots exit the spine above the associated vertebra (i.e. the C6 nerve root exits above the C6 vertebra).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] By evaluating what nerve root of the cervical spine is injured, the affected muscle groups and dermatomes can be determined.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This informs the evaluator as to what activities may be limited as a result of the injury.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This is typically done at 72 hours post-injury; exams done prior to this time have been found to be inaccurate due to the presence of swelling and other confounding factors.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] When classifying an individual's level of function, there are numerous functional assessment tools that may be used in a clinical setting and it is often up to the clinician's discretion as to which tools are used.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] A comprehensive list of these tools may be found on the ShirleyRyan AbilityLab website.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Spinal cord injuries are classified as complete or incomplete by the American Spinal Injury Association (ASIA) classification.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The ASIA scale grades patients based on their functional impairment as a result of the injury, grading a patient from A to D.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This has considerable consequences for surgical planning and therapy.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] After a comprehensive neurologic exam testing segments of the body corresponding to spinal nerve roots, the examiner will determine the patient's motor level and sensory level (e.g. motor level C6, sensory level C7).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] These levels are unique for the patient's left and right side.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This level is assigned based on the lowest (closest to the patient's feet) intact motor and sensory level.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] After this assignment, a neurological level of injury (NLI) is determined.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The NLI is the lowest segment with intact sensory and motor function provided there is normal sensory and motor function above this segment.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] As in the above ASIA chart, a complete spinal cord injury is any injury which has absent motor and sensory function in the sacral segments S4 and S5.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This is verified during the physical exam by the absence of all three of: voluntary anal contraction, deep anal pressure, and pinprick+light touch sensation in the perineal area.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] S4 and S5 are both sacral nerve roots found at the lowest portion of the spinal cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In simpler terms, "complete" is meant as a way to express that the spinal cord is injured such that no signal, motor or sensory, is carried to or from the level of injury to these lower levels of the spinal cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Incomplete spinal cord injuries result in varied post injury presentations.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] There are three main syndromes described, depending on the exact site and extent of the lesion.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Brown-Séquard syndrome: hemisection of the spinal cord with resultant loss in: a.) ipsilateral proprioception, vibration, and motor control below the level of injury b.) complete sensory loss at the level of injury c.) contralateral pain and temperature loss.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Anterior cord syndrome: a lesion of the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, most commonly due to ischemia.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This typically presents with loss of pain, temperature, and motor function at and below the level of injury.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Cauda equina syndrome: a lesion of the lumbosacral nerve roots that may spare the spinal cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] As these nerve roots are lower motor neurons, a flaccid lower limb paralysis is typically seen along with loss of bowel and bladder reflexes, varying degrees of impairment of sensation, and loss of sacral reflexes (bulbocavernosus reflex, anal wink).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Conus medullaris syndrome: a lesion similar to cauda equina syndrome however this lesion is typically found higher in the cord.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This presents clinically similarly to cauda equina syndrome however there may be intact sacral reflexes.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Unlike cauda equina, the unique location of this syndrome leads it to present with mixed upper and lower motor neuron signs.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] For most patients with ASIA A (complete) tetraplegia, ASIA B (incomplete) tetraplegia and ASIA C (incomplete) tetraplegia, the International Classification level of the patient can be established without great difficulty.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The surgical procedures according to the International Classification level can be performed.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In contrast, for patients with ASIA D (incomplete) tetraplegia it is difficult to assign an International Classification other than International Classification level X (others).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Therefore, it is more difficult to decide which surgical procedures should be performed.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] A far more personalized approach is needed for these patients.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Decisions must be based more on experience than on texts or journals.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The results of tendon transfers for patients with complete injuries are predictable.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] On the other hand, it is well known that muscles lacking normal excitation perform unreliably after surgical tendon transfers.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Despite the unpredictable aspect in incomplete lesions, tendon transfers may be useful.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The surgeon should be confident that the muscle to be transferred has enough power and is under good voluntary control.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Pre-operative assessment is more difficult to assess in incomplete lesions.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Patients with an incomplete lesion also often need therapy or surgery before the procedure to restore function to correct the consequences of the injury.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] These consequences are hypertonicity/spasticity, contractures, painful hyperesthesias and paralyzed proximal upper limb muscles with distal muscle sparing.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Spasticity is a frequent consequence of incomplete injuries.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Spasticity often decreases function, but sometimes a patient can control the spasticity in a way that it is useful to their function.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The location and the effect of the spasticity should be analyzed carefully before treatment is planned.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] An injection of botulinum toxin (Botox) into spastic muscles is a treatment to reduce spasticity.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] This can be used to prevent muscle shortening and early contractures.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Over the last ten years, an increase in traumatic incomplete lesions is seen, due to the better protection in traffic.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Upper limb paralysis refers to the loss of function of the elbow and hand.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] When upper limb function is absent as a result of a spinal cord injury it is a major barrier to regain autonomy.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] People with tetraplegia should be examined and informed concerning the options for reconstructive surgery of the tetraplegic arms and hands.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Delayed diagnosis of cervical spine injury has grave consequences for the victim.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] About one in 20 cervical fractures are missed and about two-thirds of these patients have further spinal-cord damage as a result.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] About 30% of cases of delayed diagnosis of cervical spine injury develop permanent neurological deficits.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In high-level cervical injuries, total paralysis from the neck can result.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] High-level tetraplegics (C4 and higher) will likely need constant care and assistance in activities of daily living (ADLs), such as getting dressed, eating, and bowel/bladder care.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Individuals with C5 injuries retain some function in their biceps, deltoids, and other muscles; they typically can perform many ADLs including feeding, bathing, and grooming but require total assistance with bowel/bladder care.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Even in complete spinal cord injury, it is common for individuals to recover up to 1 level of motor function.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Even with "complete" injuries, in some rare cases, through intensive rehabilitation, function can be regained through "rewiring" neural connections, as in the case of actor Christopher Reeve.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In the case of cerebral palsy, which is caused by damage to the motor cortex either before, during (10%), or after birth, some people with incomplete tetraplegia are gradually able to learn to stand or walk through physical therapy.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Tetraplegics can improve muscle strength by performing resistance training at least three times per week.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Combining resistance training with proper nutrition intake can greatly reduce co-morbidities such as obesity and type 2 diabetes.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] There are an estimated 17,700 spinal cord injuries each year in the United States; the total number of people affected by spinal cord injuries is estimated to be approximately 290,000 people.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In the US, spinal cord injuries alone cost approximately $40.5 billion each year, which is a 317 percent increase from costs estimated in 1998 ($9.7 billion).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The estimated lifetime costs for a 25-year-old in 2018 is $3.6 million when affected by low tetraplegia and $4.9 million when affected by high tetraplegia.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In 2009, it was estimated that the lifetime care of a 25-year-old rendered with low tetraplegia was about $1.7 million, and $3.1 million with high tetraplegia.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] About 1,000 people are affected each year in the UK (~1 in 60,000—assuming a population of 60 million).
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] The condition of paralysis affecting four limbs is alternately termed *tetraplegia* or *quadriplegia*.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Quadriplegia combines the Latin root *quadra*, for "four", with the Greek root πληγία *plegia*, for "paralysis".
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Tetraplegia uses the Greek root τετρα *tetra* for "four".
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In the past, "tetraplegia" and "quadriplegia" were used interchangeably in the medical literature.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Medical literature favors using "tetraplegia" as the standardized term, as it is frowned upon to mix Greek and Latin roots, although "quadriplegia" remains in use.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] "Tetraplegia", meaning the paralysis of four limbs, may be confused with "tetraparesis", meaning the weakness of four limbs.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] In medicine, it is important to not use these terms when making a diagnosis.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] When diagnosing and classifying spinal cord injuries, the ASIA classification is used to distinguish between weakness vs. no weakness, and to classify neurologically complete vs. incomplete lesions.
[src:chicken-fight/quadriplegic] Use of "tetraparesis" is discouraged as it inaccurately describes an incomplete lesion and incorrectly implies tetraplegia applies only to cases of complete lesions.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] In schools which use a house system a feature of the school is the competition between the houses; this is especially brought out during sporting events such as an inter-house sports day.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Games that are played on school sports days can be wide and varied.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] They can include straightforward sprints and longer races for all age groups as well as egg and spoon races.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Three-legged races are run as well as sack races, wheelbarrow races, and parent and child races.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Long jumps and high jumps are also held.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Additional games are traditionally run in Ireland, and the UK, such as horseshoes.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] In India, sports days are held for 2–3 days.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] These include games like football, cricket, throw ball, dodge ball, volleyball, track and field, basketball etc.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] These sports days are held between the various houses in a particular school.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] In India, many traditional games such as kho-kho, kabaddi and march-past are played.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Sports day, called *undōkai* (運動会) in Japanese, is usually held on a Saturday or Sunday in Japanese schools.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] These practices, and the sports days themselves, normally take place on the schools' fields, which provide little relief from the heat and sun.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Some schools have responded by scheduling their sports days during cooler months and by encouraging their students to drink water regularly.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Currently, the event occurs most often in the autumn (September/October), or in the spring (May/June).
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] In elementary schools in Hokkaidō, the event is usually held between the later part of May and the earlier part of June.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Sport is a significant part of Pakistani culture.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Cricket is the most popular sport, while field hockey, polo, and squash are also popular.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Many well funded private and government schools hold a Sports Day, when track and field events like running, relay races, high jump, long jump, discus and shot-put are held.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] These sports are generally played in front of an audience of parents who witness the Sports day events.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] If the children are divided by house in the school's system, then the various houses also compete against each other for enough points and medals to win that Sports day's events.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Traditional sports like kabaddi and other well-known games are also played.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism, now has control over the Pakistan Sports Board.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] The PSB controls all 39 sporting federations.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] The Pakistan Sports Board is supported by the Pakistan Sports Trust, which assists hard up players and associations so they can continue participating in sports.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Over recent years there has been an increase in sporting activity in Pakistan, with Pakistani sportsmen and women participating at many national and international events.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Also, more international tournaments now take place in Pakistan.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] The size of the teams Pakistan sends, and the number of events they participate in, such as the Olympic Games, Asian Games, World Games, and Commonwealth Games has increased since the turn of the century.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Sports Day in Russia is held on the second Saturday in August.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Sports day is a national holiday, held every second-Tuesday of February every year.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] The Olympic Committee is tasked with organizing the large-scale nationwide activities that are held all over Qatar, and include a wide variety of sports such as; football, basketball, tennis, marathons, open walks, as well as regional sports such as camel riding.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Other venues of sports day include Aspire Zone, Katara, The Pearl, among others.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Sports day's popularity extends to the point that Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al-Thani, Qatar's Emir is casually seen participating in events.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Many large organizations have sports days for their employees.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] One notable example is His Majesty's Civil Service in the UK, which holds a number of departmental sports days.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] There have been a number of controversies surrounding school sports days since the late 20th century, many of which have been publicised by the media.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] Some schools have abolished or heavily altered sports days on the grounds that they are too competitive and may damage pupils' self-esteem, with some commentators calling for the event to be banned due to the public humiliation caused to those children who are not gifted athletically.
[src:chicken-fight/sports-day] This view has been condemned as "political correctness" by many commentators, notably by journalist Melanie Phillips in her 1996 book *All Must Have Prizes*, a book heavily criticised by reviewers for its alleged prejudiced, fact-less and distorted analyses.
